accesskeys-1.title: `[accesskey]` values are not unique
accesskeys-1.description: Access keys let users quickly focus a part of the page. For proper navigation, each access key must be unique. [Learn more about access keys](https://dequeuniversity.com/rules/axe/4.10/accesskeys).

aria-allowed-role-2.title: Uses ARIA roles on incompatible elements
aria-allowed-role-2.description: Many HTML elements can only be assigned certain ARIA roles. Using ARIA roles where they are not allowed can interfere with the accessibility of the web page. [Learn more about ARIA roles](https://dequeuniversity.com/rules/axe/4.10/aria-allowed-role).

aria-valid-attr-value-3.title: `[aria-*]` attributes do not have valid values
aria-valid-attr-value-3.description: Assistive technologies, like screen readers, can't interpret ARIA attributes with invalid values. [Learn more about valid values for ARIA attributes](https://dequeuniversity.com/rules/axe/4.10/aria-valid-attr-value).

target-size-4.title: Touch targets do not have sufficient size or spacing.
target-size-4.description: Touch targets with sufficient size and spacing help users who may have difficulty targeting small controls to activate the targets. [Learn more about touch targets](https://dequeuniversity.com/rules/axe/4.10/target-size).

td-has-header-5.title: `<td>` elements in a large `<table>` do not have table headers.
td-has-header-5.description: Screen readers have features to make navigating tables easier. Ensuring that `<td>` elements in a large table (3 or more cells in width and height) have an associated table header may improve the experience for screen reader users. [Learn more about table headers](https://dequeuniversity.com/rules/axe/4.10/td-has-header).
